Diagnosis.
Pseudorostral horns relatively short (
Fig. 21A–D
). Hepatic, lateral and branchial spines long; median row with 5 spines: 3 gastric, 1 cardiac, 1 intestinal; 2 strong spines on posterior carapace margin (
Fig. 21A–D
). Surface of thoracic sternum relatively smooth, with very low rounded granules (
Fig. 50A
). Chela of adult male with distinct carina on dorsal and ventral margins (
Fig. 54A
). Ambulatory meri in adults relatively stout, short (
Fig. 21A–D
). G1 gently curved (
Fig. 23A–C
).
